Three bugs found driving an actual busybox build through an in-process box make:

1. CURDIR was the engine's PROCESS cwd, not the make's working_dir, so a Makefile
   computed srctree/`include` paths against the wrong dir (busybox failed with
   "scripts/Kbuild.include: No such file or directory"). Thread the working_dir
   into the bootstrap. (Standalone rkati's CURDIR comes from main.rs and is
   unaffected.)

2. Recipe worker threads and the brush recipe thread had the default 2 MiB stack;
   a recursive sub-make's kati parse/eval of a big Makefile recurses deeply and
   overflowed it (ckati relies on the 8 MiB main stack). Give both 64 MiB.

3. Startup race: serve printed "listening" and ran FUSE/net init while the dead
   prior daemon's socket still sat at the path; control::serve only removed+bound
   the real socket afterward. A client connecting in that window hit the stale
   dead socket → "no engine running". Bind the real socket EARLY (under the
   instance lock, before init) via control::bind_listener, so the file only
   appears once it's the live listener — connects queue in the backlog until the
   accept loop runs. serve() now takes the pre-bound listener.

Box suite green.

